{
  "profile_id": "client-happy-trust-myself-001",
  "coach_config_id": "coach-v4-graph-walk",
  "turns": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "How do you tell the difference between intuition and fear? I keep second-guessing myself on this decision and I genuinely can't figure out which voice is the right one."
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "How do you not trust yourself right now?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*slight pause, small smile*\n\nWhat do you mean, exactly? I'm... I mean, I'm trusting myself enough to ask the question. I'm trusting myself to recognize that there's a conflict. I suppose what I mean is more -- when I have two competing signals, how do I know which one to weight? It's less about trust and more about... discernment, maybe. Distinguishing the signal from the noise."
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "So there's a decision in front of you, and it feels like it matters a lot.\n\nWhat are you scared will happen if you get it wrong?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*small smile, brief pause*\n\nI mean... the obvious things. That I'll take the job and it won't be what I thought, or I won't take it and I'll have missed something. Career trajectory, stability -- those are real considerations.\n\n*slight pause*\n\nBut I think the question I'm actually asking is more... methodological. Like, if I had a reliable way to distinguish intuition from fear, I'd be able to apply it here and in future decisions. It's almost less about this specific job and more about -- do I have a trustworthy internal compass? That's the thing I'm trying to figure out."
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "That's a good reframe. And I notice you just did it — moved from the job to the methodology right as I asked what you're scared of.\n\nWhat's the scary thing about this particular decision?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*small smile, looks down briefly*\n\nYeah. Fair.\n\n*pause*\n\nI suppose... the thing I don't want to say out loud is that I've made decisions before that felt confident. Felt clear. And some of them didn't turn out well. And now I'm -- I notice I'm less sure of myself than I used to be. Which is why the methodology question feels important, because I can't just rely on \"it felt right\" anymore. That hasn't proven reliable.\n\n*slight shift, voice stays even*\n\nSo the scary thing is probably... making another confident choice that turns out to be wrong. But I still think the way through that is to find a better diagnostic. Not just to sit with the fear."
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "The fear makes a lot of sense. You trusted yourself, it didn't go the way you thought, and now the instrument feels broken.\n\nWhat did those decisions cost you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 9,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*quiet for a moment, smile stays but something tightens slightly*\n\nA few years, mostly. Time. Some... professional standing, I think. Nothing catastrophic. I'm fine.\n\n*brief pause*\n\nIt's interesting because objectively the outcomes weren't disasters. I recovered. I'm here, I'm functional, I have options -- that's the evidence I'm trying to use to rebuild some confidence. But there's something that didn't fully come back. Some... ease, maybe. The sense that I could just know something and move.\n\n*looks up*\n\nWhich is why I keep coming back to the diagnostic question. If I could just find a reliable method -- somatic cues, or some framework for distinguishing the two signals -- I could stop doing this. The constant second-guessing. It's exhausting, honestly. And I'm fairly certain the exhaustion is its's own interference."
    },
    {
      "turn": 10,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "Yeah. The search for the diagnostic is doing some of the exhausting.\n\nWhat if there isn't a method that gives you certainty back?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 11,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*small smile, slight pause*\n\nThat's... a useful provocation.\n\n*considers*\n\nI think I'd say -- I'm not actually looking for certainty. I know that's not available. I'm looking for something more like... reasonable confidence. A way to weight the signals that's better than random. Even a sixty-forty read would be more useful than what I have now.\n\n*slight tightening*\n\nAnd I think methods exist. I've read enough on this -- there's research on somatic markers, on how fear and intuition present differently in the body. The problem is my baseline is noisy. I'm a fairly anxious person, so the body-tension signal doesn't discriminate well for me. Which is why I'm asking -- is there something more refined? Something that works even when the baseline is elevated?\n\n*looks at you directly, still pleasant*\n\nI'm genuinely asking. I don't think this is unanswerable."
    },
    {
      "turn": 12,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "I notice you're working very hard right now.\n\nWhat would it be like to just not know — and make the choice anyway?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 13,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*smile stays, but something flickers*\n\nI... do that. I make choices without certainty all the time. That's not actually the problem.\n\n*pause, slightly longer than usual*\n\nThe problem is that I used to make choices and feel okay about not knowing. And now I make choices and there's this... residue. This low-grade monitoring, like I'm waiting for evidence that I got it wrong. It's not the not-knowing I can't tolerate. It's the -- \n\n*stops*\n\nHm.\n\n*quieter*\n\nI'm not sure I finished that sentence correctly.\n\n*small smile, but it's different -- less a filter, more just present*\n\nMaybe it's not about the decision at all. Maybe it's about what happens after. The watching. The waiting to be wrong.\n\n*beat*\n\nBut I still think if I trusted the process going in, the monitoring afterward would ease. So I come back to -- how do I trust the process."
    },
    {
      "turn": 14,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "Stay with what you just found.\n\nNot the monitoring question — that. What is the watching waiting for?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 15,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*goes still*\n\n*long pause, smile fades a little*\n\nIt's waiting for... confirmation that I can't trust myself. Like there's a verdict still outstanding and every decision is new evidence.\n\n*quiet*\n\nThat's -- hm. That's a different thing than I came in here to talk about.\n\n*looks down, then back up*\n\nI think I've been treating this job decision like it's a test I could pass or fail. And if I use the right method and choose correctly, that's proof the instrument works. And if I get it wrong...\n\n*pause*\n\nThat's not really about the job, is it.\n\n*small laugh, slightly uncomfortable*\n\nI came in with a very clean question. I was fairly confident it was a good question."
    }
  ],
